{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:52:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18617"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79495"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11349"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64817"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"10225"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26343"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26350"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27190"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79495","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79495"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe articulation between the femoral head and the acetabulum is undertaken by a particular type of synovial joint.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of joint at this location?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ball and socket","Hinge","Pivot","Plane","Saddle"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis articulation represents a \u003Cstrong\u003Eball and socket joint\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by a spherical head fitting into a complementary cup-shaped depression. This structural arrangement enables movement in three axes: sagittal (flexion/extension), coronal (abduction/adduction), and rotational.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlternative joint types are less suitable:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHinge joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Restricts movement to a single plane, exemplified by the elbow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlane joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Facilitates sliding movements between flat articular surfaces, as seen between carpals\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPivot joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Enables rotation around a single axis, demonstrated by the atlas-axis joint\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaddle joint\u003C/strong\u003E - Features reciprocal concave-convex surfaces, illustrated by the thumb\u0027s base\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe extensive mobility afforded by ball and socket architecture is crucial for efficient locomotion and postural control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Synovial joints are categorised into six distinct types based on their anatomical structure and permitted movements.","The hip articulation permits triaxial movement due to its ball and socket configuration.","Among synovial joints, the ball and socket configuration enables the most extensive range of motion."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64817"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions",